column1: Appendix S1 Time series of the long-term experiment
Worksheet 3 Transformed time series used in our Nature 2008 paper (species abundances and nutrients)
Note for those who wish to make use of these freely available data in their publications or presentations:
please cite the Ecology Letters publication of Beninca et al. as source of the data

column15: The data presented in this excel sheet were used in the analysis of Beninca et al. (Nature 2008).
The dataset covers the period from 16/06/1991 (= day 340) until 20/10/1997 (= day 2658).
The data presented in this worksheet are the fully transformed data.
The units of measurement are dimensionless, for all transformed data on this worksheet
The following steps illustrate the applied transformation (see the Supplementary Information of Beninca et al. Nature 2008):
1. The original data were interpolated by hermite cubic interpolation to obtain data with equidistant time intervals of 3.35 days
2. Nitrogen and phosphorus concentrations were transformed to equivalent units of 'biomass' using Redfield ratios.
3. Some timeseries showed long sequences of zeros values (i.e. cyclopoids, calanoids, protozoa, filamentous diatoms, ostracods, harpacticoids)
We shortened these time series by removing these sequences of zeros values.
4. All time series were rescaled by a fourth-rooth power transformation, to suppress sharp peaks

5. We removed long-term trends from some of the time series (i.e. bacteria, harpacticoids, ostracods, dissolved inorganic nitrogen, soluble reactive phosphorus) using a sliding window with a Gaussian kernel of  300 days.
6. All time series were normalized by subtraction of the mean and division by the standard deviation
